{
  "id": "L09",
  "title": "Inviting a Colleague for Coffee",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "tip",
      "text": "Time to make a friend! In this lesson, you'll ask a colleague for a coffee. This is a perfect way to have a 'gezellig' moment, a key Dutch concept for a cozy, friendly atmosphere."
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E01",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Hoi",
        "meaning": "Hi"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V01",
      "data": {
        "Druk": "Busy"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V02",
      "data": {
        "Deze week": "This week"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E02",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Heb je het druk?",
        "meaning": "Are you busy?"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "pronunciation",
      "item_id": "L09_P01",
      "data": {
        "word": "druk",
        "phonetic": "/drʏk/",
        "tip": "The 'u' sound is short and sharp, similar to the 'u' in 'duck'."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V03",
      "data": {
        "De koffie": "The coffee"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V04",
      "data": {
        "Lekker": "Tasty, nice"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E03",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Vind je ... lekker?",
        "meaning": "Do you like...?"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "tip",
      "text": "In Dutch, you use 'Vind je ... lekker?' to ask if someone likes to eat or drink something. It's a very common phrase!"
    },
    {
      "type": "interactive_scenario",
      "scenario_id": "L09_S01",
      "title": "Starting the Conversation",
      "setting": "You're at the coffee machine with your colleague, Anna. Start a conversation.",
      "conversation_flow": [
        {
          "title": "Ask if she is busy this week",
          "chatbot_message": "Hoi!",
          "extract_info": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Ask if she likes coffee",
          "chatbot_message": "Nee, niet druk.",
          "extract_info": null
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V05",
      "data": {
        "Drinken": "To drink"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E04",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Ik drink",
        "meaning": "I drink"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E05",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Jij drinkt",
        "meaning": "You drink"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E06",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Wil je...?",
        "meaning": "Do you want...?"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "tip",
      "text": "When you use 'Wil je...?', the second verb (like 'drinken') goes to the end of the sentence. For example: 'Wil je koffie drinken?'"
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V06",
      "data": {
        "Vrijdag": "Friday"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E07",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Op vrijdag",
        "meaning": "On Friday"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V07",
      "data": {
        "Drie": "Three"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V08",
      "data": {
        "Uur": "Hour / o'clock"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E08",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Om drie uur",
        "meaning": "At three o'clock"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "pronunciation",
      "item_id": "L09_P02",
      "data": {
        "word": "vrijdag",
        "phonetic": "/ˈvrɛidɑx/",
        "tip": "The 'v' is soft, like in 'view'. The 'g' at the end is a soft, throaty sound, typical in Dutch."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "interactive_scenario",
      "scenario_id": "L09_S02",
      "title": "Making the Invitation",
      "setting": "Anna isn't busy and she likes coffee! Now is your chance to invite her.",
      "conversation_flow": [
        {
          "title": "Invite her to have coffee on Friday",
          "chatbot_message": "Ja, ik vind koffie lekker.",
          "extract_info": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Suggest a time (3 o'clock)",
          "chatbot_message": "Ja, leuk!",
          "extract_info": null
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E09",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Oké",
        "meaning": "Okay"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "tip",
      "text": "To confirm a plan, you can simply state the day and time again. For example: 'Oké, vrijdag om drie uur'."
    },
    {
      "type": "vocabulary",
      "item_id": "L09_V09",
      "data": {
        "Leuk": "Nice, fun, great"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E10",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Tot dan",
        "meaning": "See you then"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "pronunciation",
      "item_id": "L09_P03",
      "data": {
        "word": "leuk",
        "phonetic": "/løːk/",
        "tip": "The 'eu' sound is unique to Dutch. Try to say 'uh' while rounding your lips like you're saying 'ooh'."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "expression",
      "item_id": "L09_E11",
      "data": {
        "phrase": "Leuk, tot dan!",
        "meaning": "Great, see you then!"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "interactive_scenario",
      "scenario_id": "L09_S03",
      "title": "Finalizing the Plan",
      "setting": "Anna has agreed to coffee at 3 o'clock. Now, confirm the details.",
      "conversation_flow": [
        {
          "title": "Confirm the day and time",
          "chatbot_message": "Drie uur is goed.",
          "extract_info": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Say 'Great, see you then!'",
          "chatbot_message": "Perfect. Vrijdag om drie uur.",
          "extract_info": null
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}